us.ihmc.euclid.referenceFrame

Class FrameVector3D

  • java.lang.Object

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Clearable, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.EpsilonComparable<FrameVector3D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometricallyComparable<FrameVector3D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometryObject<FrameVector3D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Settable<FrameVector3D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Transformable, FixedFrameTuple3DBasics, FixedFrameVector3DBasics, FrameChangeable, FrameTuple3DBasics, FrameTuple3DReadOnly, FrameVector3DBasics, FrameVector3DReadOnly, ReferenceFrameHolder, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple3D.interfaces.Tuple3DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple3D.interfaces.Tuple3DReadOnly, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple3D.interfaces.Vector3DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple3D.interfaces.Vector3DReadOnly

    public class FrameVector3D
extends java.lang.Object
implements FrameVector3DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometryObject<FrameVector3D>
    FrameVector3D is a 3D vector expressed in a given reference frame.

    In addition to representing a Vector3DBasics, a ReferenceFrame is associated to a FrameVector3D. This allows, for instance, to enforce, at runtime, that operations on vectors occur in the same coordinate system. Also, via the method FrameChangeable.changeFrame(ReferenceFrame), one can easily calculates the value of a vector in different reference frames.

    Because a FrameVector3D extends Vector3DBasics, it is compatible with methods only requiring Vector3DBasics. However, these methods do NOT assert that the operation occur in the proper coordinate system. Use this feature carefully and always prefer using methods requiring FrameVector3D.

      • geometricallyEquals

        public boolean geometricallyEquals(FrameVector3D other,
                                   double epsilon)
        Tests if this and other represent the same vector 3D to an epsilon.

        Two vectors are considered geometrically equal if they are at a distance of less than or equal to epsilon.

        Note that this.geometricallyEquals(other, epsilon) == true does not necessarily imply this.epsilonEquals(other, epsilon) and vice versa.

        Specified by:
        geometricallyEquals in interface us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometricallyComparable<FrameVector3D>
        Parameters:
        other - the other vector 3D to compare against this. Not modified.
        epsilon - the maximum distance that the two vectors can be spaced and still considered equal.
        Returns:
        true if the two vectors represent the same geometry, false otherwise.
        Throws:
        ReferenceFrameMismatchException - if other is not expressed in the same reference frame as this.
